**Update**: as we have guessed, the problem is due to `Add` contract being different! You have to use the contract EXACTLY as it is, as seen in the github link above. The compiler actually tells you to do `super.init()` in there, but doing that will change the verify key too.

`zkApp.deploy` will require a parameter, even though it does not in the preset code; you can give
```
{zkappKey: zkAppPrivateKey}
```
for that.

it finally works ❤️

we are connecting to the existing contract, so it is not our deployed one, but the public key of their contract. when you fetch the state (current number in the contract) you should see something around 188 (at the time of writing)

this is a big gotcha! If the `snarkyJS version` used when you deployed your smart contract is the different from the one used when you are running your client, then the verification keys won't match.
they should unless its a major breaking change (per semver) and/or major protocol upgrade

Thanks everyone for this discussion. In general, it's on us to make sure that snarkyjs updates DON'T change constraints in contract code, so that existing contracts can still create proofs for old deployed vks, using the newer snarkyjs version. IF we ship such a breaking change, it's our responsibility to clearly call that out in the changelog, and to bump the minor version (which signals a breaking change until we're at 1.0)

However, this time it seems we messed that up. But now we're more aware of this problem, and we'll try hard to not break existing contracts like that again

As for contracts with different code not being able to interact with the deployed ones -- that's of course expected, and a GOOD thing. you don't want some hacker to change your contract code on their machine, and still successfully interact with it 😄
